@incollection{SINFIELD201641,
abstract = {Ongoing tectonic continental collision between the Indian subcontinent and Eurasia is the main driving force molding and creating snow- and rain-fed mountain watersheds and ground-water basins in Afghanistan. All large cities, as well as rural, agricultural-based populations of Afghanistan draw water from aquifers within tectonically controlled, alluvium-filled structural basins. The underlying geologic fabric controls ground-water occurrence and changing climate will dramatically change watershed natural conditions Also human-caused contamination and salinization of aquifers, recharge reduction along alluvial aquifers and canal systems, and overuse of fresh-water resources, negatively affect many downstream and cross-border rivers and alluvial aquifers. Conflict increases impacts by reducing government ability to control and manage aquifer over-pumping, especially from high capacity, engine-powered well pumps that supply water for illicit opium poppies. To overcome obstacles, first steps are to understand natural underlying geologic and hydrologic conditions and limitations controlling water availability. Sustainable approaches to managing water resources in Afghanistan must be directed by underlying natural conditions. Cities, populations, and economics will always be focused on these structurally controlled valleys and their alluvial aquifers. Relatively inexpensive, potable, and bacteriologically safe drinking water occurs in deep aquifers that cannot be ignored and developing this valuable resource correctly will significantly improve health and economics in Afghanistan. Technology to access water sources must be applied correctly because the new mud-lubricated, rotary drill-rigs can drill deeper, and with larger well pumps, can increase detrimental water withdrawals. Irrigation and watershed management programs for Afghanistan should use: (1) new passive-seismic technology to conduct inexpensive yet effective ground-water exploration, (2) mud-lubricated, rotary drilling techniques for Afghan cities, and (3) improved karez repair and rehabilitation. Robust governance, focused security, and capacity-building goals, based on underlying natural conditions and limitations, help reduce threats and improve downstream and transboundary water quality and quantity issues.},
